<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,151,1148]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,340,226,252]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[350,615,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="titthion">
<emphasis box="[350,615,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Americabaetis titthion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is until now endemic to southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1075,1150,226,252]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. Nymphs are present in shallow areas above rocks, in moderate to fast current (
<figureCitation box="[792,880,264,290]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–30" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1396,1420]" captionTargetBox="[176,1411,433,1370]" captionTargetId="figure-252@10.[170,1417,421,1375]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 27–30. General aspect of Americabaetis nymphs’ habitat. 27. A. mecistognathus, sp. nov.; 28. A. alphus and A. longetron; 29. A. labiosus; 30. A. titthion." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302619/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The meso and metasternal projections, typical of this species [see Fig. 51 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty, W. P." box="[500,895,301,327]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" pagination="156 - 169" refId="ref6916" refString="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty, W. P. (1996) Taxonomy of the Neotropical Genus Americabaetis, New Status (Insecta: Ephemeroptera: Baetidae). Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 31, 156 - 169." type="journal article" year="1996">Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty (1996)</bibRefCitation>
], probably aids the nymph to withstand in this kind of habitat. At the Parque Nacional do Caparaó, where it is abundant, this is the only species of mayfly found above 
<quantity box="[304,400,376,402]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" unit="m" value="2250.0">2250 m</quantity>
.a.s.l.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,151,1148]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">
Although only females of this species have been described (Salles 
<emphasis box="[995,1048,413,438]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">et al</emphasis>
. 2003), the vestiges of the meso and metaesternal projections should also be encountered in male adults once these protuberances are found in nymphs of both sexes. This characteristic would be enough to distinguish male imagos of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[1248,1369,488,513]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="titthion">
<emphasis box="[1248,1369,488,513]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">A. titthion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[365,534,525,550]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[365,534,525,550]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Americabaetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,151,1148]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">
<bibRefCitation author="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty, W. P." box="[197,610,562,588]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" pagination="156 - 169" refId="ref6916" refString="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty, W. P. (1996) Taxonomy of the Neotropical Genus Americabaetis, New Status (Insecta: Ephemeroptera: Baetidae). Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 31, 156 - 169." type="journal article" year="1996">Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, as well as 
<bibRefCitation author="Dominguez, E. &amp; Molineri, C. &amp; Pescador, M. L. &amp; Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C." box="[744,1035,562,588]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" pagination="646" refId="ref6608" refString="Dominguez, E., Molineri, C., Pescador, M. L., Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C. (2006) Ephemeroptera of South America. In: Adis, J., Arias, J. R., Rueda-Delgado, G. &amp; Wantzen, K. M. (Eds), Aquatic Biodiversity of Latin America. Vol. 2. Pensoft, Moscow-Sofia, p. 646." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Domínguez 
<emphasis box="[888,940,562,587]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
, described the setae at the apex of the paraglossa of this species as simple. However, we examined nymphs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[1035,1152,600,625]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="titthion">
<emphasis box="[1035,1152,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">A. titthion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from different localities and concluded that these setae are pectinate, just as in the other species of the genus that live in areas with moderate to fast current above rocks (i.e., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[670,806,674,699]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="labiosus">
<emphasis box="[670,806,674,699]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">A. labiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Salles &amp; Raimundi &amp; Boldrini &amp; Souza-Franco, 2010" authorityName="Salles &amp; Raimundi &amp; Boldrini &amp; Souza-Franco" authorityYear="2010" box="[867,1089,674,699]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mecistognathus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[867,1089,674,699]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">A. mecistognathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1106,1203,674,700]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1106,1203,674,700]" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). At least in South America, species that live in a similar habitat, such as those of the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy" authorityYear="1924" box="[1060,1171,712,737]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Baetodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1060,1171,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Baetodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Demoulin" authorityName="Demoulin" authorityYear="1966" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Camelobaetidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1231,1435,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Camelobaetidius</emphasis>
Demoulin
</taxonomicName>
, exhibit the same kind of setae at the same place. According to Batista 
<emphasis box="[1108,1159,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">et al</emphasis>
. (2006), these mayflies should be assigned to the grazer functional feeding group, once they use the tip of its mouthparts, as collectors, to remove periphyton. The presence of that kind of setae at the apex of the paraglossa should be regarded as a convergence among these genera, and a possible sinapomorphy among these three species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[151,320,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,320,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="27">Americabaetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
